SmProcessing

Class ComputedParams

  • java.lang.Object
    • SmProcessing.ComputedParams

  • public class ComputedParams
extends java.lang.Object
    The computed parameters class calculates the computed parameters for records where the acceleration exceeds a threshold (default is 5% g) at any point. The values computed are bracketed duration, duration interval, Arias intensity, Housner intensity, channel RMS, and cumulative absolute velocity.

        dtime - time interval between samples in seconds
        inThreshold - percentage of g to qualify as strong motion record

      • ComputedParams

        public ComputedParams()
        This is an alternate constructor for use when calculating Housner intensity. These computed parameters are calculated during V3 processing and uses the velocity spectrum at 5% damping for its input array. There is no check here for the computed parameters threshold, and it's assumed that Housner intensity will only be calculated on records that met the computed parameters threshold.

    • Method Detail

      • calculateComputedParameters

        public boolean calculateComputedParameters()
        This method performs the calculations for all computed parameters except Housner Intensity. It returns true if the bracketed duration calculation found at least one value greater than the input threshold (5%g default), which indicates that the calculations were performed. If the return is false, all computed parameters are set at 0.
        Returns:
        true if calculations performed, false if no strong motion detected

      • calculateHousnerIntensity

        public double calculateHousnerIntensity(double[] sv,
                                        double[] T)
        Calculate Housner Intensity, using the 5% damping velocity spectrum created during V3 processing. The calculation is over the interval from 1 to 2.5 seconds. Since the sv is calculated only at 91 separate periods, the integration is performed on this abbreviated set of values. The 91 periods includes a value at 1 second but no 2.5 second value, so the 2.4 and 2.6 second values are averaged to get a value at 2.5 seconds.
        Parameters:
        sv - the velocity spectrum at 5% damping
        T - the 91 period values as index into the sv array
        Returns:
        the calculated Housner intensity value
